{"title_page": "Bridewell (New York City jail)", "text_new": "{{short description|Municipal prison in New York City}}\n{{Other uses|Bridewell (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Old Bridewell, New York, America. Coloured lithograph by H.R Wellcome V0014022.jpg|thumb|\"The Old Bridewell, which formerly stood in the Park, between the City Hall and Broadway\"]]\nThe '''Bridewell''' was a municipal [[prison]] built in 1768 on the site now occupied by [[City Hall Park]] in the [[Civic Center, Manhattan|Civic Center]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]].\n\nAccording to the [[Oxford English Dictionary]], Bridewell is a common English noun referred both to a gaol in which prisoners were held, or a workhouse to which they were confined.  The term was used for a number of jails in the [[Thirteen Colonies]]. \n\nConstruction on the New York City Bridewell began in 1768, although the building was not completed until after the end of the [[American Revolutionary War]].<ref name=\"BlackHistory\">{{cite book|last1=Black|first1=George Ashton|title=The History of Municipal Ownership of Land on Manhattan Island|date=1897|publisher=Columbia University Press|page=31}}</ref> Even though it was incomplete, the British used the jail to house [[prisoner of war|prisoners of war]] during the Revolutionary War.<ref name=\"hosm\">{{cite book |editor1-last=Wright |editor1-first=Otis Olney |title=History of Swansea, Massachusetts, 1667-1917 |date=1917 |publisher=Town of Swansea |page=54 |url=https://archive.org/stream/historyofswansea00wrig#page/54/mode/1up |accessdate=13 June 2018|oclc=1018149266}}</ref>  It stood until it was replaced by [[The Tombs]] in 1838; some of the dressed stone blocks from the Bridewell were used to construct The Tombs.<ref name=\"FourWalls\">{{cite web|title=Four Walls, City Hall Park|url=http://forgotten-ny.com/2013/06/four-walls-city-hall-park/|website=forgotten-ny.com|publisher=Forgotten New York|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref><ref>Carrott, Richard G ''The Egyptian revival: its sources, monuments, and meaning, 1808\u20131858'' University of California Press, 1978 {{ISBN|0-520-03324-8}} p.165</ref>  \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Civic Center, Manhattan}}\n{{coord|40.71380|-74.0062|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-NY|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Jails in New York City]]\n[[Category:1768 establishments in New York]]\n[[Category:Government buildings in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Demolished buildings and structures in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1768]]\n[[Category:Civic Center, Manhattan]]\n\n\n{{manhattan-struct-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Municipal prison in New York City}}\n{{Other uses|Bridewell (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Old Bridewell, New York, America. Coloured lithograph by H.R Wellcome V0014022.jpg|thumb|\"The Old Bridewell, which formerly stood in the Park, between the City Hall and Broadway\"]]\nThe '''Bridewell''' was a municipal [[prison]] built in 1768 on the site now occupied by [[City Hall Park]] in the [[Civic Center, Manhattan|Civic Center]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]].\n\nAccording to the [[Oxford English Dictionary]], Bridewell is a common English noun referred both to a gaol in which prisoners were held, or a workhouse to which they were confined.  The term was used for a number of jails in the [[Thirteen Colonies]]. \n\nConstruction on the New York City Bridewell began in 1768, although the building was not completed until after the end of the [[American Revolutionary War]].<ref name=\"BlackHistory\">{{cite book|last1=Black|first1=George Ashton|title=The History of Municipal Ownership of Land on Manhattan Island|date=1897|publisher=Columbia University Press|page=31}}</ref> Even though it was incomplete, the British used the jail to house [[prisoner of war|prisoners of war]] during the Revolutionary War.<ref name=\"hosm\">{{cite book |editor1-last=Wright |editor1-first=Otis Olney |title=History of Swansea, Massachusetts, 1667-1917 |date=1917 |publisher=Town of Swansea |page=54 |url=https://archive.org/stream/historyofswansea00wrig#page/54/mode/1up |accessdate=13 June 2018|oclc=1018149266}}</ref>  It stood until it was replaced by [[The Tombs]] in 1838; some of the dressed stone blocks from the Bridewell were used to construct The Tombs.<ref name=\"FourWalls\">{{cite web|title=Four Walls, City Hall Park|url=http://forgotten-ny.com/2013/06/four-walls-city-hall-park/|website=forgotten-ny.com|publisher=Forgotten New York|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref><ref>Carrott, Richard G ''The Egyptian revival: its sources, monuments, and meaning, 1808\u20131858'' University of California Press, 1978 {{ISBN|0-520-03324-8}} p.165</ref>  \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|40.71380|-74.0062|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-NY|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Jails in New York City]]\n[[Category:1768 establishments in New York]]\n[[Category:Government buildings in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Demolished buildings and structures in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1768]]\n[[Category:Civic Center, Manhattan]]\n\n\n{{manhattan-struct-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Epicgenius", "label": "safe", "comment": "add navbox", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bridewell_(New_York_City_jail)"}
